<BODY>
<TEXT>
russian president vladimir putin says he will pardon and release
american businessman edmond pope. a russian court convicted pope
<TIMEX2 val="2000-12-06" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">wednesday</TIMEX2> on espionage charges and sentenced him to <TIMEX2 val="P20Y" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">20 years in
prison</TIMEX2>. pope denied the charges and appealed to putin for clemency
saying he needs urgent medical aid. he has suffered from a rare type
of bone cancer. the pennsylvania man has been jailed in russia since
<TIMEX2 val="2000-04" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">april</TIMEX2> on charges he tried to obtain secret plans for a high-speed
torpedo. pope, who runs a technology information company, insisted
the plans were freely available. the clinton administration is
praising the decision to release pope. 
</TEXT>
